				Two unique facts about Spain
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				The Running of the Bulls, held in the city of Pamplona every July since 1385 is one of the oldest and most dangerous traditions. During the event, six bulls chase mozos (a group of young men) who traditionally wear white with a red
sash while running around the city streets trying not to get trampled. The origin of the event started in the 14th century when the bulls had to be transported to the markets to be sold. Men had to use tactics like scaring or exciting the cattle to make them go to their destination faster. During this transport some young men would get in front of the bulls and run until they got to their pens. In time this “transport of the bulls” became an event with spectators.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
	
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Pablo Picasso (1881-1973) was Spain’s most famous artist. He was a painter, sculptor and print maker. He co-founded the Cubist movement and is regarded to be the most influential artists of the 20th century. Picasso produced over 147,000 works of art, many of which are masterpieces that earned him an immense fortune and fame during his long life.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
